Fixing Persistent Windows Installer Popups at Startup After Browser Hijacker Cleanup

## Summary

This issue started as a recurring Windows Installer popup appearing every time the PC rebooted. Three small Windows Installer error windows appeared at login with the message:

> This installation package could not be opened. Verify that the package exists and that you can access it, or contact the application vendor to verify that this is a valid Windows Installer package.

At first, the issue looked like leftover Google Chrome installer corruption because Autoruns showed several broken Chrome-related startup entries. However, deeper inspection showed the real cause was not Chrome and not Microsoft Gaming Services. The root cause was leftover browser-hijacker persistence through malicious scheduled tasks launching missing MSI installers from suspicious ProgramData folders.

---

## Background

Earlier, the system had a Chrome browser hijacker that redirected searches through suspicious domains such as:

* `nextgeeker.com`
* `directsearchapp.com`

The hijacker had used multiple persistence techniques:

* Fake Chrome profile paths
* Browser search-engine hijack
* Suspicious Chrome policies
* Fake browser-like folders
* Scheduled tasks
* Microsoft Defender exclusions
* Locked leftover Chrome installation files

Previously discovered suspicious paths included:

```text
%LOCALAPPDATA%\DGoogle
%LOCALAPPDATA%\DDapps
%LOCALAPPDATA%\EMicrosoft
C:\ProgramData\Chromnius
C:\ProgramData\ChromniusEdge
C:\Program Files (x86)\GeneralAISupport2Solutions
```

After the original cleanup, the browser hijack was gone, but Windows Installer popups started appearing after reboot.

---

## Initial Symptom

On every reboot/login, Windows displayed three installer error windows.

The error message was:

```text
This installation package could not be opened.
Verify that the package exists and that you can access it,
or contact the application vendor to verify that this is a valid Windows Installer package.
```

Because three windows appeared, the suspicion was that three startup/persistence entries were trying to launch missing installer packages.

