## Step 1: Checked Autoruns Startup Entries

Autoruns showed broken Chrome-related startup entries in yellow, marked as `File not found`.

Examples:

```text
Google Chrome — File not found
Google Chrome — File not found
Google Platform Experience Helper — File not found
GoogleUpdaterTaskUser147... — File not found
```

These were initially disabled, but after reboot, the Windows Installer popups still appeared.

Conclusion: the broken Chrome entries were leftovers, but they were not the main trigger.

---

## Step 2: Checked Windows Installer Events

PowerShell was used to inspect recent Windows Installer events:

```powershell
Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{
  LogName='Application'
  ProviderName='MsiInstaller'
  StartTime=(Get-Date).AddHours(-2)
} | Select-Object TimeCreated, Id, ProviderName, Message | Format-List
```

The output repeatedly showed:

```text
C:\Program Files\WindowsApps\Microsoft.GamingServices_...\gameinputredist.msi
Product: Microsoft GameInput
Reconfiguration success or error status: 0
```

This made Microsoft Gaming Services / GameInput look suspicious at first.

Gaming Services was repaired, removed, and reinstalled from the Microsoft Store. Its services were confirmed running:

```powershell
Get-AppxPackage Microsoft.GamingServices -AllUsers |
Select-Object Name, Version, PackageFullName, InstallLocation
```

```powershell
Get-Service *Gaming*,*GameInput* |
Select-Object Name, DisplayName, Status, StartType
```

Gaming Services was installed and running correctly.

Conclusion: Gaming Services was noisy in Event Viewer, but it was not the source of the three popup errors.

---

## Step 3: Identified the Real Parent Process

The key step was checking active installer processes while the popups were still open.

```powershell
Get-CimInstance Win32_Process |
Where-Object { $_.Name -match 'msiexec|installer|setup|gameinput|gaming' } |
Select-Object ProcessId, ParentProcessId, Name, CommandLine |
Format-List
```

This revealed the real cause:

```text
msiexec.exe /i "C:\ProgramData\GeneralAISupport2Solutions\GeneralAISupport2\updates\Update\Setup.msi" ADDLOCAL=MainFeature,CHROMEINSTALLER

msiexec.exe /i "C:\ProgramData\FutureSpaceThreeSolutions\FutureSpaceThree\updates\Update\Setup.msi" ADDLOCAL=MainFeature,CHROMEINSTALLER
```

The parent process was:

```text
svchost.exe -k netsvcs -p -s Schedule
```

That confirmed Task Scheduler was launching malicious or leftover installer tasks.

Conclusion: the Windows Installer popups were caused by scheduled-task persistence from the previous browser hijacker.

---

## Step 4: Killed the Bad MSI Processes

PowerShell Administrator:

```powershell
Get-CimInstance Win32_Process |
Where-Object {
  $_.CommandLine -match 'GeneralAISupport2|FutureSpaceThree|Setup\.msi|CHROMEINSTALLER'
} |
ForEach-Object {
  Stop-Process -Id $_.ProcessId -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
}
```

---

## Step 5: Found the Malicious Scheduled Tasks

PowerShell Administrator:

```powershell
$badTasks = Get-ScheduledTask | Where-Object {
  ($_.Actions | Out-String) -match 'GeneralAISupport2|FutureSpaceThree|Setup\.msi|CHROMEINSTALLER'
}

$badTasks | Select-Object TaskName, TaskPath, State, Actions | Format-List
```

The suspicious tasks found were:

```text
WorldWideWeb
{5862B490-06BF-467A-B4B1-5AA06B848048}
{EAF4CC3C-99E0-4AFE-83B1-7E9F39F4818F}
{F54E7186-50C6-42F7-ACE9-A36954AA9C7E}
```

---

## Step 6: Disabled and Deleted the Bad Scheduled Tasks

PowerShell Administrator:

```powershell
$badTasks | ForEach-Object {
  Disable-ScheduledTask -TaskName $_.TaskName -TaskPath $_.TaskPath -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
  Unregister-ScheduledTask -TaskName $_.TaskName -TaskPath $_.TaskPath -Confirm:$false -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
}
```

---

