## Final Result

After removing the malicious scheduled tasks and leftover folders:

* No more Windows Installer popups appeared after reboot
* No malicious MSI processes were running
* No suspicious scheduled tasks remained
* Microsoft Defender exclusions were blank
* Suspicious ProgramData folders were removed
* Broken Autoruns leftovers were cleaned up

The issue was resolved.

---

## Root Cause

The root cause was not Chrome itself and not Microsoft Gaming Services.

The real cause was leftover scheduled-task persistence from a previous browser hijacker. The scheduled tasks attempted to launch missing MSI installers from suspicious folders:

```text
C:\ProgramData\GeneralAISupport2Solutions
C:\ProgramData\FutureSpaceThreeSolutions
```

The MSI command included:

```text
ADDLOCAL=MainFeature,CHROMEINSTALLER
```

This strongly suggests the malware or unwanted software was attempting to reinstall or repair a fake Chrome-related component.

---

## Key Lessons

When Windows Installer popups appear at every boot:

1. Do not assume the visible app is the root cause.
2. Use Autoruns to check startup entries.
3. Use Event Viewer to inspect MSI events.
4. Use PowerShell to inspect active `msiexec.exe` command lines.
5. Check parent process IDs to see whether Task Scheduler is launching the installer.
6. Search scheduled tasks by action command, not only by task name.
7. Check Defender exclusions after any browser hijacker infection.
8. Remove orphaned scheduled tasks and suspicious folders.
9. Do not manually delete protected WindowsApps folders.
10. Run a full malware scan after cleanup.

